post_text:
Martin County Parents and Guardians,

Based on Governor Beshear’s recommendation for all K-12 public schools, the Martin County School District will begin virtually, with online classes starting August 26. All students will receive instruction via Google Classroom. Each school will release dates for parents and students to pick up Chromebooks, class schedules, and Google Classroom information. Per Governor Beshear’s recommendation, in-person learning will resume on September 28.

Moving forward, we will provide additional district-wide updates as needed. Thank you for your patience and understanding through this extraordinary time.

Thank You,



Larry James
Martin County School District Superintendent

The reason ALL of our students are eligible is because of our free school breakfast and lunch program participation. Please fill out your census so we can keep this program!!

post_text:
Warfield Elementary School Selects New Principal

Shane Stafford has been selected to serve as the next principal at Warfield Elementary School. Shane is beginning his 9th year in the Martin County School District. He has taught special education, physical and health education, and most recently served as assistant principal at Martin County Middle School. Mr. Stafford is a dedicated and resourceful educator, leader, and team member. When asked about his new role in the district, he said, “I want to ensure that the staff, students, parents, community members, and stakeholders feel valued and empowered. Working together, we can build on Warfield Elementary School’s successes.”
Mr. Stafford received his Bachelor of Arts Degree from Morehead State University, his Masters of Arts in Education from Union College, and is currently enrolled in Western Kentucky University’s Educational Leadership Program.
Welcome aboard Mr. Stafford!

post_text:
Sheldon Clark High School Names New Principal

INEZ, KY – The Sheldon Clark High School School Based Decision Making Council met in an open meeting this morning to name Martha Williams as the new principal of Sheldon Clark High School (SCHS). Martha Williams is moving into the principal position at the beginning of the school year after a successful ten years as the ATC administrator. Ms. Williams has been an educator for 21 years, with all of those years in the Martin County School District. We want to welcome her to her new role!

The high school was placed on a lockdown this morning, October 13, 2014 at approximately 9am. The Kentucky State Police were notified and responded. As of 9:51, the lock down was lifted.

The reason for the lockdown: As reported and confirmed, a 9mm cartridge was intentionally placed to initiate a lockdown. The cartridge, as immediately identified by our staff and then declared by the KSP officer, was not a live round, but part of a keychain (decorative).

March 4, 2013 at 5:10 PM ·

What a way to celebrate career and technical education (CTE) month! Ten gold, seven silver an three bronze medals were awarded at the Northeast District 11 Skills USA competition held February 22nd at the Mayo Campus of Big Sandy Community & Technical College. The theme for the conference, "prepared with the Skills America Needs" was demonstrated by each and every Martin County competitior. Skills advisores Johnnie Dials, Michael Jude and Dwayne Pack are to be commended for the excellent job they did in preparing their students for this competition. Anita Coleman served as competition coordinator for the conference. Some regional winners will progress to state Skills USA competiton to be held at the Galt House in Louisville, KY in April. Congratulations Students!

San Antonio, Texas: Austin Murphy, a junior at Sheldon Clark High School, traveled with the Kentucky delegation to compete in FBLA National Competition. Austin placed third in state competition which qualified him to advance to Texas. Competition was stiff in his event of Introduction to Technolog Concepts with 89 competitors. "I enjoyed meeting people from all different states. I was impressed with how big the FBLA organization actually is. I enjoyed competing, but stil wish I had brought home a trophy. I am preparing to qualify to go to Nationals again this year. It was such an awesome experience!" During his free time Austin enjoyed visiting the Alamo and learning about the history surrounding it. Good luck this year Austin!

Martin County Schools added 4 new photos.
July 11, 2012 at 1:35 PM ·

Recently, Austin Murphy, a sophomore at Sheldon Clark High School, attended the 2012 National Leadership Conference in San Antonio, Texas whose theme was Gateway to Greatness. At the Regional Leadership Conference in Morehead, KY, Austin placed first in Introduction to Technology Concepts and advanced on to state competition in Louisville, KY. There he placed third and became eligible to compete at the national level. There were over eight thousand students in attendance to compete. While there, Austin met with students from every state in the United States as well as the U.S. Virgin Islands, Haiti, Puerto Rico, Grand Cayman Islands, and Canada. Although he did not place in the top ten at the national level the experience was beneficial and Austin hopes to compete again next year.

post_text: Due to several areas still experiencing power outages and a need for recovery from the tornado, the Martin County School District will be closed the rest of the week for students. The Martin County School District will conduct professional learning days for the school staff members on Thursday, March 8, 2012 and Friday, March 9, 2012. Your agendas will need to be emailed to the central office for the professional learning days. The Martin County School District has made arrangements for kitchens to be opened at two(2) locations, Sheldon Clark High School and Warfield Middle School. The kitchens will be open from 8:00 a.m to 1:00 p.m. The kitchens will be open on Wednesday, March 7, Thursday, March 8 and Friday, March 9, 2012. They will be serving breakfast and lunch for our students. Please pass this information along so that everyone can make the appropriate arrangements.

Career & Technical students of Martin County ATC and Sheldon Clark High School conducted their annual “Share a Story” night on Tuesday, October 11th. The statewide Unite to Read project held by career and technical students each year promotes literacy and a joy for life-long reading. Approximately 100 primary-third grade students, parents, secondary CTE students, advisors, Food City, Pac’s Now, and Link’s staff participated in this event. “The Two Bite Club” was the book the theme of the evening was based on. This book provided students the “My Pyramid” for making healthy food choices. In addition to eating right, the book stressed exercising and having fun.

post_text: Martin County School District met 13 out of 13 target goals (100.00 Percent) on the No Child Left Behind Adequate Yearly Progress Report 2011. Increased test scores in Martin County Schools are a result of all the hard work put forth by our students and teachers last year. The district showed an 8.85% gain in reading and a 7.61 % gain in all students scoring at or above proficiency on the state required tests. Only 22 of 174 school districts (12.6%) met 100% of their No Child Left Behind (NCLB) AYP goals. According to Mr. Blackburn, this is a proud moment for our district. He would like to congratulate all the faculty, staff and students for their hard work.

September 19, 2011 at 3:44 PM ·

The SCHS JROTC Raiders Team participated in the Warhorse Competition in Yatesville KY this weekend.
During the weekend long competition, SCHS JROTC Raiders team were challenged to numerous events that tested the cadet's teamwork capabilities, strength, endurance, communication skills and survival techniques.
SFC Rodriguez took 2 team (male and female, together 23 cadets) to the overnight event.
SFC Rodriguez stated " I am very proud of our cadets. This competition was just a glimpse of what to expect in our SCHS JROTC future. We do have much work ahead of us and areas to improve to get to the top. I am especially proud to win the Tug-Of-War event during the competition, it's the first step in the right direction".
SCHS JROTC Raiders Team will head to Eastern Kentucky University in Richmond this coming weekend to test their skills at the EKU ROTC Cadet Stakes. We wish them all "Good Luck"... All for One, One for All !!!
